    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-02T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-02T01:00:00-05:00" n="235"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d235">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9132: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-02T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 2, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>354. 1. Following from Tsinanfu:<note n="28" xml:id="d235fn28">From John M.
                        Allison, Consul at Tsinan.</note>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“August 1, 4 p.m. Since the entrance into Shantung of Central Government
                            troops as reported in my July 31, 8 p.m., the local situation has become
                            serious. A large number of Chinese have attempted to leave the city and
                            it has been necessary to turn many of them back.</p>
                        <p>The Japanese Consul General stated in conversation this afternoon that he
                            had not yet given up hope of a peaceful settlement but that it was
                            necessary to prepare for the worst. Many of the official records of the
                            Japanese are being sent to Tsingtao and only approximately 650 Japanese
                            are still in the city. The Consul General further stated that he had
                            heard this morning that Central Government troops had arrived in
                            Tsinanfu today and that if such troops are stationed here in the
                            province it was deemed a cause for Japanese troops to come in. He
                            mentioned an unconfirmed report that Han Fu Chu<note n="29"
                                xml:id="d235fn29">Chairman of the Shantung Provincial
                                Government.</note> left here for the south yesterday to meet General
                            Pai Chunghsi.<note n="30" xml:id="d235fn30">Vice Commander, Chinese 5th
                                Route Army.</note> He gave it as his private opinion that foreign
                            women and children should leave Tsinanfu.</p>
                        <pb facs="0251" n="243" xml:id="pg_243"/>
                        <p>Unless I am instructed to the contrary I intend to urge American women
                            and children at interior points to go to Tsingtao or Tsinanfu and I
                            shall advise same in this city to be prepared to evacuate at a moment’s
                            notice.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>2. Embassy has replied: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“August 2, 11 a.m. Your August 1, 4 p.m. I approve of steps which you
                            have already taken. Embassy appreciates your constant efforts to keep it
                            already [<hi rend="italic">always?</hi>] advised of local
                            situation.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>3. Tokyo being informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
